'Destiny' is co-written by Williams and [[Monty Norman]] and contains the famous four-chord sequence from Norman's [[James Bond Theme]] within the song. The video that accompanied the song's release was filmed in [[Worthing]], [[West Sussex]], and uses interior shots filmed in the unique [[Dome Cinema, Worthing]].<ref>'''Destiny''' by Francon, ft. Keith Pemberton (retrieved 25 July 2018) Video: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=WMB-ReTUKLU</ref><ref>'''Destiny''' by Francon, Ft. Keith Pemberton (retrieved 25 July 2018): https://plus.google.com/collection/gpfcV</ref> A [https://soundcloud.com/wm-records/destiny-by-francon-instrumental-jb-mix 'Destiny' (Instrumental) JB-007 MIX] was also released.\n\nOn 28 July 2016, it was reported in the media that Alice Shaw (the former backing vocalist in the band You You You) passed away on 27 July 2016.<ref>Boy George reveals his devastation as close friend takes her own life (article) ''Daily Mirror'': 28 July 2016: https://www.mirror.co.uk/3am/celebrity-news/boy-george-reveals-devastation-close-8509292</ref><ref>Photographs of Alice appearing on stage with You You You in 1987 in Brighton: https://twitter.com/alifromdapally (courtesy of Alice Shaw Facebook page)</ref><ref>You You You on Brighton Beach 1987- photographs 1:https://twitter.com/alifromdapally</ref><ref>You You You on Brighton Beach 1987 photographs 2:https://twitter.com/alifromdapally</ref><ref>You You You on Brighton Beach 1987 photographs 3:https://twitter.com/alifromdapally</ref>\n\n==''Love Is Suicide'' 2020==\nOn 9 March 2020, to celebrate the 36th anniversary of his recording of ''\u2018Love Is Suicide\u2019'', Iain released a lyric video shot in [[Miami]] and [[California]], [[United States]].\n[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=u3COk-P2w0M \u2018Love Is Suicide\u2019 2020] is a homage to the Great [[American (word)|American]] Road Trip.\n\n==Discography ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center; width:10px;\"|Year\n! rowspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center; width:200px;\"|Single\n! style=\"text-align:center;\" colspan=\"2\"|Peak positions\n! rowspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center; width:40px;\"|Label\n|-\n!width=\"20\"|<small>[[UK Singles Chart|UK]]</small>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=\"3\"|1989\n|\"Voulez-Vous\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|12\" single\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|#27 (''Record Mirror'' chart)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://s1130.photobucket.com/user/Beatrice211/media/Big%20Bang%20British%20band/19092012-1_zps4254c8fb.jpg.html |title=Big Bang - Voulez Vous Single At 27 In Record Mirror Chart Photo by Beatrice211 &#124; Photobucket |publisher=S1130.photobucket.com |date= |accessdate=2014-08-06}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|White Label\n|-\n|\"Voulez-Vous\"/\"Cold Nights in Cairo\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|7\" single\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|#101 (BBC chart)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://s1130.photobucket.com/user/Beatrice211/media/Big%20Bang%20British%20band/19092012-1_zpse810ba35.jpg.html |title=Big Bang - Evening Standard, 20 September 1989, Metropolis - 80s Icons (edited By Sorrel Downer), Big Bang Celebrate Reaching No. 101 In The Charts With Their Arabic Inspired Version Of \"Voulez Vous\" By Appearing At Heaven Photo by Beatrice211 &#124; Photobucket |publisher=S1130.photobucket.com |date=1989-09-20 |accessdate=2014-08-06}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|Swanyard Records\n|-\n|\"Voulez-Vous\"/\"Cold Nights in Cairo\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|12\" single\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|#14 (end of year club chart) <ref>{{cite web|url=http://s1130.photobucket.com/user/Beatrice211/media/Big%20Bang%20British%20band/19092002-3_zps2a49d94a.jpg.html |title=1989 End Of Year London Club Chart - Big Bang Voulez Vous At Number 14 Photo by Beatrice211 &#124; Photobucket |publisher=S1130.photobucket.com |date= |accessdate=2014-08-06}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|Swanyard Records\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center; width:10px;\"|Year\n! rowspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center; width:200px;\"|Single\n! style=\"text-align:center;\" colspan=\"2\"|Peak positions\n! rowspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center; width:40px;\"|Label\n|-\n!width=\"20\"|<small>[[UK Singles Download Chart|UK]]</small>\n!width=\"20\"|<small>[[US Singles Download Chart|US]]</small>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=\"3\"|2013\n|\"I Really Miss U\" (ft. Teresa Revill)\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|single download\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|single download\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|WM Records\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center; width:10px;\"|Year\n! rowspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center; width:200px;\"|EP\n! style=\"text-align:center;\" colspan=\"2\"|Peak positions\n! rowspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center; width:40px;\"|Label\n|-\n!width=\"20\"|<small>[[UK Download Chart|UK]]</small>\n!width=\"20\"|<small>[[US Download Chart|US]]</small>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=\"3\"|2014\n|\"Arabic Circus // The Dawn Rising\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|EP download\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|EP download\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|WM Records\n|}\n\n==Tours==\n* You You You \u2013 'Stage I' ''World Domination Tour'' (1987)\n* Big Bang \u2013 ''Arabic Circus Tour'' (1989)\n\n==External links==\n* Big Bang discography:<ref>http://www.45cat.com/record/syr1</ref>\n* Big Bang: ''Arabic Circus//The Dawn Rising'':<ref>https://www.allmusic.com/album/arabic-circus-the-dawn-rising-mw0002865902</ref>\n* Big Bang: ''Arabic Circus//The Dawn Rising'' \u2013 Credits:<ref>https://www.allmusic.com/album/arabic-circus-the-dawn-rising-mw0002865902/credits</ref>\n* [https://soundcloud.com/big-bang-british-band/love-is-by-iain-williams-ft-vocals-by-lelo Love Is Suicide] by Iain Williams & the 1984 Project <ref name=\"soundcloud.com\">{{cite web|url=https://soundcloud.com/big-bang-british-band/love-is-by-iain-williams-ft-vocals-by-lelo|title=Love Is - Iain Williams & the 1984 Project (ft. vocals by Lelo)|accessdate=28 February 2018}}</ref>\n* Getty Images [https://www.gettyimages.co.uk/photos/laurence-malice?family=editorial&phrase=laurence%20malice&sort=best Laurence Malice]\n\n==Further reading==\n* ''[https://www.waterstones.com/book/the-little-big-beat-book/rory-hoy/9781912587094 The Little Big Beat Book]'' by Rory Hoy, published 10 September 2018, by New Haven Publishing Ltd, {{ISBN|9781912587094}}, pages 48\u201350, outlines Big Bang's involvement in the development of [[Big Beat]] as a musical genre. The book charts the history of Big Beat as a musical genre.<ref>''The Little Big Beat Book'' by Rory Hoy, published 10 September 2018 by New Haven Publishing Ltd: {{ISBN|9781912587094}} - The book outlines the history of [[Big Beat]] as a musical genre and contains 120 interviews with bands and musicians that helped create and produce Big Beat music. Big Bang interview pp 48\u201350: http://www.foyles.co.uk/witem/biography/the-little-big-beat-book,rory-hoy-9781912587094</ref><ref>BBC Radio 6, Craig Charles Radio Show, Craig Charles interviews Rory Hoy, writer of ''the Little Big Beat Book'':https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/m0000cnr</ref>\n* ''[https://www.waterstones.com/book/the-story-of-big-beat/rory-hoy/9781949515091 The Story of Big Beat: Bookazine]'' by Rory Hoy, published 30 July 2019, by New Haven Publishing Ltd, {{ISBN|978-1949515091}}\n\n{{Portal bar|Music|1980s|UK}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{Commons|Big Bang (British Band)}}\n\n[[Category:Alternative dance musical groups]]\n[[Category:Big beat groups]]\n[[Category:Electronic music duos]]\n[[Category:English musical duos]]\n[[Category:English synth-pop groups]]\n[[Category:Musical groups established in 1988]]\n[[Category:Musical groups from London]]\n[[Category:Nu-disco musicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|British electronic synthpop duo}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2015}}\n{{Use British English|date=August 2015}}\n\n{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n| name                = Big Bang\n| image               = Big Bang - Arabic Circus Tour, UK 1989-90.jpg\n| caption             = Big Bang performing their Arabic Circus Tour, 1989-90\n| background          = group_or_band\n| origin              = [[London]], [[England]]\n| genre               = [[Big beat]], [[electronica]], [[synthpop]], [[alternative dance]], [[nu-disco]]\n| years_active        = 1988\u20131991<br/>2013\u2013present\n| label               = WM Records, Swanyard Records\n| associated_acts     = You You You\n| website             = \n| current_members     = Laurence Malice<br/>Iain Williams\n| past_members        = Vocalists<br/>Teresa Revill (1989-1991)<br/>Jasmine Joanna Duggan (Ventura) (1989-1991)\n}}\n\n'''Big Bang''' are a British [[Electronic music|electronic]] music duo that came to prominence in the late 1980s. The band consists of Laurence Malice <ref>Laurence Malice profile: Retrieved 6 December 2018:http://www.dmcworld.net/features/laurence-malice-1/</ref> (founder of [[Trade (nightclub)|Trade]] nightclub) and Iain Williams (writer).<ref>Iain Cameron Williams: Author's Biography: https://www.amazon.com/author/iaincameronwilliams</ref><ref>Iain Cameron Williams:Amazon Japan:https://www.amazon.co.jp/Empirical-Observations-Algernon-Cameron-Williams/dp/1916146503/ref=sr_1_2?__mk_ja_JP=\u30ab\u30bf\u30ab\u30ca&keywords=the+empirical+observations+of+algernon&qid=1560261823&s=gateway&sr=8-2</ref> Based in London, the duo were signed to Swanyard Records and spearheaded the music genre known as [[big beat]].<ref>\"Classic '90s\" article by Harry Beynon (retrieved 25 October 2018) talks of Big Bang's involvement with the birth of Big Beat: https://www.thestudentplaylist.com/the-prodigy-the-fat-of-the-land/</ref>\n\n==Musical history==\n===1988: Formation and early years===\n[[File:Big Bang .jpg|thumb|Big Bang]]\n'''Big Bang''' were formed during the latter part of 1988.\n\nFrom 1986\u20131988, Laurence and Iain had previously been in a band together called [https://i1130.photobucket.com/albums/m526/Beatrice211/You%20You%20You%20British%20Band%201987-1988/YouYouYou-L-RLaurenceKarenIain1987publicityphoto.jpg You You You] along with the vocalist Karen O'Connor and backing vocalist Alice Shaw.<ref name=buzz1>''The BUZZ'' magazine, issue no.5, Spring 1987, page 87. Article ... '''You You You - It's What She Likes''' (text by Nicky Heywood, photograph of You You You by Andrew Czezowski)</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://s1130.photobucket.com/user/Beatrice211/media/You%20You%20You%20British%20Band%201987-1988/YouYouYoupublicityphotograph1987.jpg.html?sort=3&o=8 |title=You You You Photo by Beatrice211 &#124; Photobucket |publisher=S1130.photobucket.com |date= |accessdate=2014-08-06}}</ref><ref>Photographs of You You You on stage in Brighton: https://twitter.com/alifromdapally (courtesy of Alice Shaw)</ref>\nYou You You gave their first concert at a secret location in Charing Cross Road, London, in early January 1987. So secret was the venue, members of the band have since forgotten what it was called. The show was arranged as an unannounced warm-up gig before their debut at the [[Camden Palace]] on 13 January.<ref name=buzz1/><ref>''Evening Standard'', ''Ad Lib'', page 10, 13 January 1987, You You You play live at Camden Palace tonight</ref> The band billed their first series of concerts as 'Stage 1' of their 'World Domination Tour' and enlisted the help of illustrator Mark Wardel to design their publicity.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://s1130.photobucket.com/user/Beatrice211/media/You%20You%20You%20British%20Band%201987-1988/08042012-4.jpg.html?sort=3&o=4 |title=You You You - Band Illustrated By Mark Wardel, 1987, Copyright Mark Wardel Photo by Beatrice211 &#124; Photobucket |publisher=S1130.photobucket.com |date= |accessdate=2014-08-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.trademarkart.com/content/_5109713121_large.html |title=Trademark/Scene - Portraits |publisher=Trademarkart.com |date= |accessdate=2014-08-06}}</ref>\nTheir appearance at the [[Camden Palace]] attracted over 1,000 people on what the Met Office recorded as probably being England's coldest night of the 20th Century.<ref name=buzz1/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://i1130.photobucket.com/albums/m526/Beatrice211/You%20You%20You%20British%20Band%201987-1988/YouYouYoupublicityflyer1987.jpg |title=You You You - British band - 1987 concert ticket for their debut performance on 13 January at the Camden Palace, London - 'Stage 1' of their 'World Domination' tour. |publisher=I1130.photobucket.com |accessdate=2014-08-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metoffice.gov.uk/climate/uk/sw/print.html |title=Regional Climate: South West England |publisher=Met Office |date= |accessdate=2014-01-10}}</ref><ref>''Melody Maker'' LIVE! review, 24 January 1987, page 19, ''You You You, Camden Palace, London''. Live concert review by Joy Press and a photograph of Karen performing on stage at the Camden Palace, 'There is always a need... for a band like You You You'</ref>\nIt was during this tour that Karen wore her controversial conical metal bra on stage.<ref>Publicity photograph of You You You showing Karen wearing her metal conical bra which she wore on stage during the band\u2019s 1987 \u2018World Domination Tour\u2019 Stage I: [https://s1130.photobucket.com/user/Beatrice211/media/You%20You%20You%20British%20Band%201987-1988/YouYouYoupublicityphotograph1987.jpg.html You You You]</ref> Designer [[Jean Paul Gaultier]] a couple of years later designed his renowned version of the cone bra for [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]] to wear on her 1990 [[Blond Ambition World Tour]].\n[[File:You You You on stage at the Zap Club 18th April 1987.jpg|thumb|left|You You You (band) on stage at [[The Zap]] Club, [[Brighton]], 18 April 1987]]\nYou You You built up a strong following performing concerts on the club scene including three nights at the [[Hippodrome, London]] (23 January,<ref>{{cite web|title=You You You concert ticket for the Hippodrome, 23 January 1987, containing a Mark Wardel illustration of the band|url= http://i1130.photobucket.com/albums/m526/Beatrice211/You%20You%20You%20British%20Band%201987-1988/08042001-3.jpg|publisher=Photobucket.com|accessdate=2014-08-06}}</ref> 9 February and 6 April),<ref>''Evening Standard'', ''Ad Lib'', 22 January 1987, page 27, ''Beauty and the Beast'', Karen and You You You with photograph of Karen</ref><ref>''City Limits'', 29 January 1987, ''JIVETALK'', music-nightclubs, page 53, Laurence Malice interview by Rose Christie, article contains a photograph of Laurence</ref><ref>''Melody Maker'', 7 February 1987, ''Blondes have more fun'' page 7, article about You You You, with a photograph of Karen and Laurence on stage performing at the Hippodrome</ref> a show at [[Le Palace]] in Paris, which the performance artist [[Leigh Bowery]] hosted,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://i1130.photobucket.com/albums/m526/Beatrice211/You%20You%20You%20British%20Band%201987-1988/YouYouYouandLeighBoweryconcertticket1987Paris.jpg |title=French Touch |publisher=I1130.photobucket.com |accessdate=2014-08-06}}</ref> and performances at [[The Fridge (nightclub)|The Fridge]] <ref>You You You (picture) at the Fridge, London (retrieved 1 December 2017): https://plus.google.com/b/109624757875466956519/photos/photo/109624757875466956519/6494682211662426514?icm=false&iso=true&sqid=112931076803092723983&ssid=b30d612d-a633-421b-b64d-4cd23d0971da</ref> in Brixton where they appeared on stage on a huge white staircase with a troupe of synchronised dancers (filmed for Japanese TV),<ref name=buzz1/><ref>''Time Out'', page 46, 25 March 1987, You You You, current faves on the club scene appear at the Fridge on Friday, 27 March - 'special coaches to the venue will be laid on leaving Charing Cross at 10.30pm returning at 1.00am.'</ref> at Anarchy Club at [[London Astoria]], at [[The Zap]] Club in Brighton (as part of the event 'Return of the Django goes to Brighton' on 18 April),<ref>{{cite web|author=Zap Art |url=http://www.zaparchive.org/ |title=www.zaparchive.org |publisher=www.zaparchive.org |date= |accessdate=2014-01-10}}</ref><ref>''Time Out'', Night Life, Speakeasy, 18 April 1987 - Brighton - the outrageous You, You, You appear at the Zap Club in Brighton</ref> at Paradise Lost in Watford and at [[The Limelight]].<ref>''BIZ'' magazine, (''Mail on Sunday'') 21 June 1987, page 3, ''Shooting Stars'', You You You interview and a colour photograph - The audience in Watford didn't know what had hit them.'</ref><ref>''Daily Express'', ''Court In The Act'', 8 July 1987, page 23, Karen O'Connor from You You You sees herself as a sex-bomb in the Jayne Mansfield mould</ref> The band received an invitation to appear at ''The Party'' (a benefit concert held at [[Wembley Arena]] on 1 April for the first ever World AIDS Day).<ref name=buzz1/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://i1130.photobucket.com/albums/m526/Beatrice211/You%20You%20You%20British%20Band%201987-1988/youyouyou1987Buzzmagazinearticle.jpg |title=You, You, You - It's What She Likes!! |publisher=I1130.photobucket.com |accessdate=2014-08-06}}</ref> On the bill were some of the best known names in the music industry including [[Elton John]], [[George Michael]], [[Bob Geldof]], [[Meat Loaf]], [[Ben E. King]] and [[Kim Wilde]]. The show was televised to over 100 million viewers worldwide. Due to the volume of acts who performed at the event, You You You were allotted an appearance at the After-Party show held at a theatre in London's West End. The band appeared on stage alongside several pop stars including [[George Michael]], members from the cast of TV's [[Coronation Street]] and [[EastEnders]] and performers from several West End musicals including [[42nd Street (musical)]] and [[Nunsense]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kathyszaksite.com/aidsday87.html |title=Kathy's Zak Starkey Site: Stand By Me - Aids Day Benefit 1987 |publisher=Kathyszaksite.com |date= |accessdate=2014-08-06}}</ref>\nOn 12 July, You You You made a guest appearance on the [[Channel 4]] TV show [[Network 7]]. Their pop video for ''Head over Heels'' <ref>You You You stills from 'Head over Heels' Video:https://twitter.com/alifromdapally</ref> directed by Steven Chivers was premiered on the show and Karen was interviewed by presenter [[Magenta Devine]] inside a specially built caravan. On 17 December, You You You gave a special Christmas Show at the [[Hippodrome, London]] (their 4th appearance at the venue that year). It would become the band's last ever live performance.\n\nIn February 1988, You You You signed a deal with Orinoco to record a single for Major Productions under the guidance of Orinoco Studios owner Tom Astor. The Lager Brothers - Ken Thomas and [[Zeke Manyika]] (from the band [[Orange Juice (band)|Orange Juice]]) - produced two tracks with the band.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://s1130.beta.photobucket.com/user/Beatrice211/media/You%20You%20You%20British%20Band%201987-1988/19092012_zpsc3ca705a.jpg.html?sort=3&o=1 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20130216163647/http://s1130.beta.photobucket.com/user/Beatrice211/media/You%20You%20You%20British%20Band%201987-1988/19092012_zpsc3ca705a.jpg.html?sort=3&o=1 |url-status=dead |archive-date=2013-02-16 |title=EQ Magazine, April 1988, Page 20, Studio Lockout Update, 'You You You' Recording Single At Orinoco Photo by Beatrice211 &#124; Photobucket |publisher=S1130.beta.photobucket.com |date= |accessdate=2014-08-06 }}</ref> In July the project came to a halt after Karen quit the band to concentrate on her acting career. Soon after the split Laurence and Iain created Big Bang as a duo using session vocalists for recordings and live performances. The single You You You recorded titled 'How Can This be Love' was never released.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://s1130.photobucket.com/user/Beatrice211/media/You%20You%20You%20British%20Band%201987-1988/13112012_zps99b49bd7.jpg.html?sort=3&o=2 |title=You You You - Unreleased Single 'How Can This Be Love' Recorded At Orinoco Recording Studios Photo by Beatrice211 &#124; Photobucket |publisher=S1130.photobucket.com |date= |accessdate=2014-08-06}}</ref>\n\nPrior to You You You, Laurence had hosted the Pyramid Club at [[Heaven (nightclub)|Heaven]] nightclub, London<ref>Pyramid Club at Heaven hosted by Laurence Malice: https://www.islington.gov.uk//~/media/sharepoint-lists/public-records/leisureandculture/information/factsheets/20152016/201601142016tradeoftencopiedneverequalledexhibition</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://thestar.ie/laurence-malice-interview-25-years-of-trade-history/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=26 September 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160927161445/http://thestar.ie/laurence-malice-interview-25-years-of-trade-history/ |archive-date=27 September 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref> and Iain had been a member of several London-based bands including 'Dance on a Telephone'<ref>Dance On A Telephone \u2013 original concert handbill - Brixton Ace, July 11, 1983: http://www.urban75.org/brixton/history/posters7.html</ref> and 'One by One' (with whom he recorded the single ''I Kept My Promise'' released in 1984 on Discovery Records.)<ref>''I Kept My Promise'' by One by One- Catalogue entry: http://www.45cat.com/record/dis001uk</ref>\n\nIn January 1984, Iain recorded the dance track [https://soundcloud.com/big-bang-british-band/love-is-by-iain-williams-ft-vocals-by-lelo 'Love Is Suicide'] at [[Trident Studios]] in [[Soho]], [[London]], under the provisional title '''Iain Williams & the 1984 Project'''.<ref>''Love Is (Suicide)'' - https://soundcloud.com/big-bang-british-band/love-is-by-iain-williams-ft-vocals-by-lelo</ref> The track was penned by Williams and co-produced by [[Fiachra Trench]] and Iain Williams. The 9-minute recording based on repetitive chord structures was an experiment in producing a rhythmic, minimalistic dance track aimed specifically for the dance clubs. Iain cited his inspiration for the recording as coming from, ''\"various components, including the 'music with repetitive structures' principle of American composer [[Philip Glass]] along with a lyrical essence of [[George Orwell]]'s dystopian novel '[[Nineteen Eighty-Four]]' - the songs lyrics are an observation of the S&M-style relationship between the novels two main characters, Winston and Julia.\"'' An impressive line-up of musicians appeared on the recording including [[Hans Zimmer]] (on [[Fairlight CMI]] synth and [[LinnDrum]]), guitarist [[Alan Murphy]] (later of the band [[Level 42]]), lead vocals by Lelo (of the band Lelo and the Levants), with backing vocals by Shirley and Dee Lewis, and the famous Trident Studio grand piano (on which [[Rick Wakeman]] played on [[David Bowie]]'s recording of '[[Life On Mars (song)|Life On Mars]]' was played by Iain Williams.<ref>https://soundcloud.com/big-bang-british-band/love-is-by-iain-williams-ft-vocals-by-lelo</ref> In 1985, Iain produced and co-wrote the single ''The Boys Were There'' released on [[the Fridge (nightclub)|the Fridge]] nightclub indie label, Latex Records, for London-based performance artiste Yvette the Conqueror.<ref>''The Boys Were There'' by Yvette the Conqueror \u2013 Discogs catalogue entry: https://www.discogs.com/Yvette-The-Conqueror-The-Boys-Were-There/release/8510631</ref>\n\n===1989: Swanyard Records,''Voulez-Vous'' and big beat===\n\nBig Bang signed to Swanyard Records at the start of 1989. The label was founded by Margarita Hamilton owner of [[Walton Castle]] and Big Bang were the first artist to be signed to it. They released their first record on Swanyard Records (SYRTR 1)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.discogs.com/label/9466-Swanyard-Records-Ltd |title=Swanyard Records Ltd - CDs and Vinyl at Discogs |publisher=Discogs.com |date= |accessdate=2014-08-06}}</ref> in June 1989, an Arabic inspired version of the [[ABBA]] classic [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tPZct_szpuM ''Voulez-Vous''] b-side [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=sAjqSYCGg0A ''Cold Nights In Cairo''].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.discogs.com/artist/1350483-Big-Bang-7 |title=Big Bang (7) Discography at Discogs |publisher=Discogs.com |date= |accessdate=2014-08-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.vinylsearcher.com/records/28582248/big-bang-7/voulez-vous.aspx |title=Big Bang - Voulez Vous? Swanyard Records Ltd (Vinyl) at vinylsearcher |publisher=Vinylsearcher.com |accessdate=2014-01-10 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140110205752/http://www.vinylsearcher.com/records/28582248/big-bang-7/voulez-vous.aspx |archive-date=10 January 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref> It reached #101 in the BBC national chart.<ref name=ESVV>{{cite web |url=http://s1130.beta.photobucket.com/user/Beatrice211/media/Big%20Bang%20British%20band/19092012-1_zpse810ba35.jpg.html?sort=3&o=0 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20130131062129/http://s1130.beta.photobucket.com/user/Beatrice211/media/Big%20Bang%20British%20band/19092012-1_zpse810ba35.jpg.html?sort=3&o=0 |url-status=dead |archive-date=2013-01-31 |title=Big Bang - Evening Standard, 20 September 1989, Metropolis - 80s Icons (edited By Sorrel Downer), Big Bang Celebrate Reaching No. 101 In The Charts With Their Arabic Inspired Version of ''Voulez Vous'' by appearing at Heaven. Photo by Beatrice211 &#124; Photobucket |publisher=S1130.beta.photobucket.com |date=1989-09-20 |accessdate=2014-08-06 }}</ref> The single was produced by Big Bang and Steev Toth. Both 7\" and 12\" versions (plus an 'Imagine Mix' 12\" extended version) were released. The band used session vocalists on all their recordings. Lead vocals on ''[[Voulez-Vous (song)|Voulez-Vous]]'' were shared by Jasmine Duggan (Ventura) <ref>Jasmine Joanna Duggan (b 29 Feb 1968) and her mother (actress) Viviane Ventura (photograph): https://www.shutterstock.com/editorial/image-editorial/anthony-and-cleopatra-party-london-uk-20-jun-1986-9789286s</ref> and Teresa Revill and backing vocals were shared by Iain and Laurence. [[Duran Duran]] guitarist Andy Taylor played guitar on the track.<ref>Iain Williams interview regarding Big Bang recording Voulez Vous mentions Andy Taylor from [[Duran Duran]] playing on the track (retrieved 1 September 2014): http://www.bigbanguk.co.uk/#!big-bang-and-the-recording-of-voulez-vou/cvo3 {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141006192942/http://www.bigbanguk.co.uk/#!big-bang-and-the-recording-of-voulez-vou/cvo3 |date=6 October 2014 }}</ref> A 12\" white label had previously been released several months earlier.<ref>''Record Mirror'', 22 January 1989, page 39, review, \"Voulez-Vous\" by Big Bang - limited edition white label. 'Extremely limited white label pressing by Iain Williams and Laurence Malice with Abba sound-a-like female support of indeed that groups obviously still catchy classic in a Democratic 3 mixed Near Eastern flavoured smoothly trotting 126 BPM revival about which we will probably be hearing more'</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.discogs.com/Big-Bang-Voulez-Vous/release/3365540 |title=Big Bang (7) - Voulez Vous? (Vinyl) at Discogs |publisher=Discogs.com |date= |accessdate=2014-01-10}}</ref> Mixed by Democratic 3, [https://soundcloud.com/big-bang-british-band/voulez-vous-by-big-bang-democratic-3-dance-mix 'Voulez-Vous' (Democratic 3 Mix)] reached #1 in certain club charts throughout the UK and #27 in a ''[[Record Mirror]]'' chart.<ref name=RM040389>''Record Mirror'', 4 March 1989, page 40, ''Voulez-Vous'' (12\" white label) by Big Band, #27 in chart</ref> Also, a [https://soundcloud.com/laurence-malice/voulez-vous 'Voulez-Vous (Rare mix)'] was distributed specifically to dance clubs.\n\nIt was Iain Williams who coined the musical term [[big beat]] to describe the band's sound and explained the concept during an interview with the journalist Alex Gerry for an article in the London magazine ''Metropolitan'' (issue 132, page 9, 6 June 1989) under the heading, 'Big Bang in Clubland. Could Big Beat be the 1989 answer to Acid House?'.<ref>''Metropolitan'' magazine (issue 132, page 9, 6 June 1989)'BIG BANG IN CLUBLAND. Could BIG BEAT be the 1989 answer to ACID HOUSE?</ref> Big Bang's sound consisted of various experimental musical elements including heavy hard rock drum beats and synthesizer-generated loops as well as an added suggestion of European influences that at times had a trance-like quality. Their agent 10 x Better released a press release detailing their musical influences that included [[Dalida]], [[Warda Al-Jazairia]], [[ABBA]], [[Tamla Motown]] and 70s Euro disco.<ref>''Big Bang press release'', 1989, issued by the agency 10 x Better. The press release accompanied promotional copies of their single \"Voulez-Vous\". It lists Big Bang's musical influences and explains their Big Beat concept.</ref> Big Bang always stated ''Cold Nights In Cairo'' gave a better impression of the [[big beat]] sound they were aiming for than their recording of ''[[Voulez-Vous (song)|Voulez-Vous]]'' did. Club DJs picked up on this and both tracks became club floor-fillers. The concept of the [[big beat]] sound was later picked up on and adapted by many club DJs and went on to become widely used by many successful musicians throughout the 1990s.\n\n===1989: Arabic Circus Tour===\n[[File:Laurence Malice and Iain Williams of Big Bang performing on stage during their 1989 Arabic Circus Tour-horz.jpg|thumb|left|Laurence Malice (left) and Iain Williams (right) of Big Bang performing on stage during their 1989 Arabic Circus Tour]]\nDuring 1989, Big Bang performed several concerts to publicise the release of ''[[Voulez-Vous (song)|Voulez-Vous]]'' with their lavish Arabic Circus Tour that consisted of various circus acts including acrobats, one-wheel bicycle riders, fire-eaters, jugglers, flying trapeze artists and a belly-dancing troupe.<ref name=to200989>''Time Out'', 20 September 1989, page 5 & 93, Big Bang Arabic Circus Tour</ref> Big Bang were joined on stage by the vocalists Teresa Revill and Jasmine Ventura. [[File:Big Bang on stage during their UK Arabic Circus Tour, 1989.jpg|thumb|Big Bang on stage during their Arabic Circus Tour, 1989]]  Shows were performed at the [[Hippodrome, London]] in Leicester Square where [[Steve Strange]] hosted the night and it was said [[Grace Jones]] threatened to jump on stage to upstage the band <ref>''Capital'' newspaper, page 15, 15 December 1989</ref> and at the Paramount City in Soho (formerly the [[Windmill Theatre]]), at the [[Hammersmith Palais]] in Hammersmith, and at [[Heaven (nightclub)|Heaven]] nightclub with DJ's [[Mark Moore]] (creator of the band [[S'Express]]) and [[Colin Faver]] who on his [[Myspace]] page cites Big Bang as being one of his many musical influences.<ref name=ESVV/><ref name=to200989/><ref>''Capital'' newspaper, page 9, 15 September 1989, 'Heaven will play host to the first ever appearance of Big Bang on 20 September'</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.myspace.com/colinfaver |title=Colin Faver &#124; Listen and Stream Free Music, Albums, New Releases, Photos, Videos |publisher=Myspace.com |date= |accessdate=2014-01-10}}</ref><ref>''Capital'' newspaper, 29 September 1989, issue 412, front page (quarter page photograph of Big Bang's Arabic Circus Tour in concert on stage at Heaven)</ref><ref>''Evening Standard'', 20 September 1989, Big Bang appear at Heaven with their Arabic Circus Tour</ref> ''The Arabic Circus Tour'' also performed at a special Ball held in a massive disused West London warehouse hosted by the performance artist [[Leigh Bowery]] with experimental musician/vocalist [[Danielle Dax]] and American punk singer and former [[Andy Warhol]] prot\u00e9g\u00e9 [[Jayne County]] appearing as supporting artists on the bill.\n[[File:Big Bang - Arabic Circus Tour, UK.jpg|thumb|left|Big Bang on stage during their Arabic Circus Tour, 1989]]\n[[File:Iain Williams - Big Bang - Arabic Circus Tour, UK, 1989-90.jpg|thumb|right| Iain Williams on stage at the [[Hippodrome, London]] during Big Bang's Arabic Circus Tour, 1989]]\n\n===1990\u201391: Recording their album & the International Song Festival===\n'''1990''': Throughout 1990 Big Bang concentrated on writing and recording new material with the intention of releasing an album. In October Laurence opened [[Trade nightclub]] at Turnmills in London. Trade was the first all-night after-hours nightclub in Britain and became legendary.<ref>{{cite web |author=Facebook |url=http://blogs.independent.co.uk/tag/laurence-malice/ |title=Laurence Malice Blog Posts &#124; Topic Tags &#124; Independent Blogs |publisher=Blogs.independent.co.uk |date=2011-10-24 |accessdate=2014-01-10 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111225191645/http://blogs.independent.co.uk/tag/laurence-malice/ |archive-date=25 December 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nAlso in 1990, Laurence appeared in the [[Dead or Alive (band)|Dead or Alive]] video for their single \"[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=c4quTMMCJL0 Your Sweetness (Is Your Weakness)]\" from their album ''[[Fan the Flame (Part 1)]]''. Laurence appears in drag playing a cello in the nightclub scenes.<ref>Your Sweetness is your Weakness by [[Dead or Alive (band)|Dead or Alive]] \u2013 Laurence Malice appears at 1:46 and 3:06 and 3:17 and 3:23 https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=c4quTMMCJL0</ref>\n\nOn 16 November 1990, Big Bang accompanied by vocalist Jasmine Duggan (Ventura) were flown over to Ireland to represent the United Kingdom in the 13th International Song Festival where they performed their self-penned song [https://soundcloud.com/big-bang-british-band/one-more-chance-by-big-bang-ft-teresa-revell ''One More Chance''].<ref>'''One More Chance''' by Big Bang - original recording of Big Bang performing '''One More Chance''' :https://soundcloud.com/big-bang-british-band/one-more-chance-by-big-bang-ft-teresa-revell</ref> It was the first time the song had been heard in public. The festival, held in [[Cavan]], lasted for two days and was compered by the Irish commentators [[George Hamilton (commentator)]] and [[Larry Gogan]]. The Romanian singer Ricky Dandel gave a guest performance during the festival.<ref>{{cite web|author=Serpi Lucian  |url=http://www.rickydandel.com/biographies.htm |title=Official Site - Biographies |publisher=Ricky Dandel |date= |accessdate=2014-01-10}}</ref>\nThe final was held on 17 November. Big Bang came second in the competition and first for their performance. During their stay in Ireland Big Bang gave several radio, TV and newspaper interviews.\n\nUpon their return to London Big Bang parted company with Swanyard Records over musical differences. The band immediately secured interest from [[London Records]] who commissioned them to record a single at The Music Station in Fulham. With a new producer at the helm Big Bang laid down the backing track to ''One More Chance''.\n[[File:Laurence Malice - Big Bang - Arabic Circus Tour, UK, 1989-90.jpg|thumb|left|Laurence Malice on stage at the [[Hippodrome, London]] during Big Bang's Arabic Circus Tour]]\n'''1991''': Although Big Bang never officially disbanded, at the tail end of 1991 Laurence and Iain decided to concentrate on their careers away from the band. The new material they wrote and recorded for their intended album titled 'Theory' was never released.\n\n===2010\u201312: Renewed interest===\n[[File:Teresa Revill - Big Bang - Arabic Circus Tour, UK, 1989-90.jpg|thumb|Teresa Revill - Big Bang]]\nInterest in the band has recently increased. In 2010, digitally remastered bootleg CDs of ''[[Voulez-Vous (song)|Voulez-Vous]]'' and ''Cold Nights in Cairo'' by Big Bang began to appear in America selling for as much as \u00a345.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cdandlp.com/liste/index.cfm?fmt=0&categ_rech=0&seller=0&lng=2&search_mode=1&what=artiste&tete=big-bang&srt=4&page=8&filtre_rech=1&changeselect=0 |title=BIG BANG : vinyl, cd, maxi, lp, ep for sale on |publisher=Cdandlp.com |date=2009-11-02 |accessdate=2014-01-10}}</ref>\nIn November 2010, in Tokyo, Japan, the DJ's Dr. Rob & Matt Best of RightRightRight included ''Cold Nights in Cairo'' in their Dr. Rob - Lonely Acid 2010 mix No. 36.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://samurai.fm/rightrightright/rightrightright-36-dr-rob-lonely-acid-and-then-the-drugs-took-hold |title=Dr Rob - Lonely Acid &#124; RightRightRight |publisher=samurai.fm |date=2010-11-03 |accessdate=2014-01-10 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110720200254/http://samurai.fm/rightrightright/rightrightright-36-dr-rob-lonely-acid-and-then-the-drugs-took-hold |archive-date=20 July 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\nIn December 2010, The Groove Room included a mix of ''[[Voulez-Vous (song)|Voulez-Vous]]''  by Big Bang in their Party Mix 1 <ref>{{cite web|author=The Groove Room |url=http://thegrooveroom.blogspot.com/2010/12/party-mix-1.html |title=grooveroom - 60s-90s nostalgia radio show: Party Mix 1 |publisher=Thegrooveroom.blogspot.com |date=2010-12-30 |accessdate=2014-01-10}}</ref>\n\n2012: The original 1989 12\" 'Imagine mix' version of ''[[Voulez-Vous (song)|Voulez-Vous]]'' by Big Bang is included on the 2012 ''EuroNixMix Dance Mix 4''. The mix is available on YouTube<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Yw7ReKfYtWk |title=EuroNick61 Old Skool Dance Mix 12 |publisher=YouTube |date=2012-02-20 |accessdate=2014-01-10}}</ref>\n\nJuly 2012: Big Bang - ''[[Voulez-Vous (song)|Voulez-Vous]]'' 2012 the 'Rare Mix' 12\" version was uploaded onto SoundCloud.<ref>''Voulez-Vous'' by Big Bang - the 'Rare Mix' 12\" version: (retrieved 18 October 2014):https://soundcloud.com/laurence-malice/voulez-vous</ref>\n\n===2013: ''I Really Miss U''===\n\nBig Bang - [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=lKKDzDEEAzM 'I Really Miss U'] (ft. Teresa Revill)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/gb/album/i-really-miss-u-feat.-teresa/id692714233?ls=1 |title=iTunes - Music - I Really Miss U (feat. Teresa Revill) - Single by Big Bang |publisher=Itunes.apple.com |date= |accessdate=2014-01-10}}</ref>\n\nOn 26 August 2013, Big Bang issued a press statement announcing the release of their first single in over two decades. The emphatically catchy ''I Really Miss U'' features lead vocals by Teresa Revill. The single was released on 26 August 2013 and is available worldwide as a download from iTunes, Rhapsody, Amazon <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/I-Really-Miss-U/dp/B00EPEP674 |title=I Really Miss U: Big Bang feat. Teresa Revill: MP3 Downloads |publisher=Amazon.com |date=2013-08-26 |accessdate=2014-01-10}}</ref> etc. The media immediately dubbed it a [[nu-disco]] track. A lyric video to accompany the song can be seen on YouTube.\n\n==2014: ''Arabic Circus // The Dawn Rising (EP)''==\n'''Arabic Circus // The Dawn Rising''' (Big Bang EP) <ref>Tracks 1 and 2 from ''Arabic Circus // The Dawn Rising'' on SoundCloud (retrieved 29 September 2014): https://soundcloud.com/big-bang-british-band/sets/big-bang-arabic-circus-the</ref>\n\nOn 1 July 2014, Big Bang announced via their website that they were releasing a new six-track EP (extended play).<ref>Big Bang - ''Arabic Circus // The Dawn Rising'': https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/arabic-circus-the-dawn-rising-ep/886195513</ref>\n'''Arabic Circus // The Dawn Rising''' <ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/gb/album/arabic-circus-dawn-rising/id886195513 |title=iTunes - Music - Arabic Circus // The Dawn Rising - EP by Big Bang |publisher=Itunes.apple.com |date= |accessdate=2014-08-06}}</ref> was officially released as a digital download (mp3) on 4 August 2014 on WM Records and is available worldwide.<ref>Juno listing of Arabic Circus by Big Bang http://www.junodownload.com/products/big-bang-arabic-circus-the-dawn-rising/2509481-02/</ref> This is Big Bang's first EP and is a collection of songs/tracks taken from the soundtrack to their ''Arabic Circus''. It is 21 minutes in length. On 2 July, Big Bang released a promotional video short on their website and YouTube to accompany the EP's release,<ref>Big Bang - ''Arabic Circus // The Dawn Rising'': https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=mrRJ3xIwuAw</ref> using a remixed version ''The Symphonic Mix'' of their track ''Trail of the Bedouins'' to accompany the video soundtrack.\n\n===''Arabic Circus // The Dawn Rising'' track listing===\n{{Track listing\n| collapsed       = no\n| headline        =\n| extra_column    = Arrangement\n| total_length    = 21:03\n\n| all_writing     =\n| all_lyrics      =\n| all_music       =\n\n| title1          = [https://soundcloud.com/big-bang-british-band/voulez-vous-by-big-bang Voulez-Vous] <ref>Voulez Vous on SoundCloud (retrieved 30 August 2014) https://soundcloud.com/big-bang-british-band/sets/big-bang-arabic-circus-the</ref>\n| writer1         = [[Benny Andersson]] and [[Bj\u00f6rn Ulvaeus]]\n| lyrics1         = B. Andersson / B. Ulvaeus\n| music1          = B. Andersson / B. Ulvaeus\n| extra1          = Big Bang / Steev Toth\n| length1         = 3:48\n\n| title2          = [https://soundcloud.com/big-bang-british-band/tell-me Tell Me] <ref>Tell Me (featuring Jasmine Ventura) on SoundCloud (retrieved 30 August 2014) https://soundcloud.com/big-bang-british-band/sets/big-bang-arabic-circus-the</ref>\n| writer2         = Iain Williams and Laurence Malice\n| lyrics2         = I. Williams / L. Malice\n| music2          = I. Williams\n| extra2          = Iain Williams / Simon Thomas\n| length2         = 4:07\n\n| title3          = [https://soundcloud.com/big-bang-british-band/higher-higher-by-big-bang Higher and Higher]\n| note3          = Democratic 3 mix\n| writer3         = Iain Williams and Laurence Malice\n| lyrics3         = I. Williams / L. Malice\n| music3          = I. Williams\n| extra3          = Iain Williams / Simon Thomas/ Democratic 3\n| length3         = 4:06\n\n| title4          = [https://soundcloud.com/big-bang-british-band/cold-nights-in-cairo Cold Nights in Cairo]\n| note4           = S. Proctor mix\n| writer4         = Big Bang\n| lyrics4         = (instrumental)\n| music4          = I. Williams / L. Malice\n| extra4          = Big Bang / S. Proctor\n| length4         = 3:40\n\n| title5          = [https://soundcloud.com/big-bang-british-band/tm2-by-big-bang-sahara-city-mix TM2]\n| note5           = Sahara City mix\n| writer5         = Iain Williams\n| lyrics5         = (instrumental)\n| music5          = I. Williams\n| extra5          = Iain Williams / Simon Thomas\n| length5         = 3:59\n\n| title6          = [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=mrRJ3xIwuAw Trail of the Bedouins]\n| note6           =  The Badaw\u012b (\u0628\u062f\u0648\u064a) Mix\n| writer6         = Iain Williams\n| lyrics6         = (instrumental)\n| music6          = I. Williams\n| extra6          = Iain Williams\n| length6         = 1:23\n}}\n\n===''Arabic Circus // The Dawn Rising'' - release history===\n''Arabic Circus // The Dawn Rising'' was released on WM Records in various countries worldwide in 2014.\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Region\n! Date\n! Label\n! Format\n! Catalog\n|-\n| [[Australia]], [[New Zealand]]\n| 4 August 2014\n| WM Records\n| Digital download\n| WMR0003\n|-\n| [[Japan]]\n| 4 August 2014\n| WM Records\n| Digital download\n| WMR0003\n|-\n| [[United Kingdom]], [[Europe]]\n| 4 August 2014\n| WM Records\n| Digital download\n| WMR0003\n|-\n| [[United States]], [[Canada]]\n| 4 August 2014\n| WM Records\n| Digital download/CD<ref>Arabic Circus//The Dawn Rising audio CD on Amazon:(retrieved 4 February 2015):https://www.amazon.com/Arabic-Circus-The-Dawn-Rising/dp/B00QXXYCHK</ref>\n| WMR0003\n|}\n\n===2015-present===\n\n==''Destiny'' by Francon==\nIn 2015, Iain Williams released the song [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=WMB-ReTUKLU \u2018Destiny\u2019] under the alias FRANCON with featured vocals by Keith Pemberton.<ref>'''Destiny''' by Francon, ft. Keith Pemberton (retrieved 25 July 2018): https://open.spotify.com/album/0hxLeAfd6kfzpxkMfPaF7X</ref> 'Destiny' is co-written by Williams and [[Monty Norman]] and contains the famous four-chord sequence from Norman's [[James Bond Theme]] within the song. The video that accompanied the song's release was filmed in [[Worthing]], [[West Sussex]], and uses interior shots filmed in the unique [[Dome Cinema, Worthing]].<ref>'''Destiny''' by Francon, ft. Keith Pemberton (retrieved 25 July 2018) Video: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=WMB-ReTUKLU</ref><ref>'''Destiny''' by Francon, Ft. Keith Pemberton (retrieved 25 July 2018): https://plus.google.com/collection/gpfcV</ref> A [https://soundcloud.com/wm-records/destiny-by-francon-instrumental-jb-mix 'Destiny' (Instrumental) JB-007 MIX] was also released.\n\nOn 28 July 2016, it was reported in the media that Alice Shaw (the former backing vocalist in the band You You You) passed away on 27 July 2016.<ref>Boy George reveals his devastation as close friend takes her own life (article) ''Daily Mirror'': 28 July 2016: https://www.mirror.co.uk/3am/celebrity-news/boy-george-reveals-devastation-close-8509292</ref><ref>Photographs of Alice appearing on stage with You You You in 1987 in Brighton: https://twitter.com/alifromdapally (courtesy of Alice Shaw Facebook page)</ref><ref>You You You on Brighton Beach 1987- photographs 1:https://twitter.com/alifromdapally</ref><ref>You You You on Brighton Beach 1987 photographs 2:https://twitter.com/alifromdapally</ref><ref>You You You on Brighton Beach 1987 photographs 3:https://twitter.com/alifromdapally</ref>\n\n==''Love Is Suicide'' 2020==\nOn 9 March 2020, to celebrate the 36th anniversary of his recording of ''\u2018Love Is Suicide\u2019'', Iain released a lyric video shot in [[Miami]] and [[California]], [[United States]].\n[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=u3COk-P2w0M \u2018Love Is Suicide\u2019 2020] is a homage to the Great [[American (word)|American]] Road Trip.\n\n==Discography ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center; width:10px;\"|Year\n! rowspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center; width:200px;\"|Single\n! style=\"text-align:center;\" colspan=\"2\"|Peak positions\n! rowspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center; width:40px;\"|Label\n|-\n!width=\"20\"|<small>[[UK Singles Chart|UK]]</small>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=\"3\"|1989\n|\"Voulez-Vous\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|12\" single\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|#27 (''Record Mirror'' chart)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://s1130.photobucket.com/user/Beatrice211/media/Big%20Bang%20British%20band/19092012-1_zps4254c8fb.jpg.html |title=Big Bang - Voulez Vous Single At 27 In Record Mirror Chart Photo by Beatrice211 &#124; Photobucket |publisher=S1130.photobucket.com |date= |accessdate=2014-08-06}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|White Label\n|-\n|\"Voulez-Vous\"/\"Cold Nights in Cairo\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|7\" single\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|#101 (BBC chart)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://s1130.photobucket.com/user/Beatrice211/media/Big%20Bang%20British%20band/19092012-1_zpse810ba35.jpg.html |title=Big Bang - Evening Standard, 20 September 1989, Metropolis - 80s Icons (edited By Sorrel Downer), Big Bang Celebrate Reaching No. 101 In The Charts With Their Arabic Inspired Version Of \"Voulez Vous\" By Appearing At Heaven Photo by Beatrice211 &#124; Photobucket |publisher=S1130.photobucket.com |date=1989-09-20 |accessdate=2014-08-06}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|Swanyard Records\n|-\n|\"Voulez-Vous\"/\"Cold Nights in Cairo\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|12\" single\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|#14 (end of year club chart) <ref>{{cite web|url=http://s1130.photobucket.com/user/Beatrice211/media/Big%20Bang%20British%20band/19092002-3_zps2a49d94a.jpg.html |title=1989 End Of Year London Club Chart - Big Bang Voulez Vous At Number 14 Photo by Beatrice211 &#124; Photobucket |publisher=S1130.photobucket.com |date= |accessdate=2014-08-06}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|Swanyard Records\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center; width:10px;\"|Year\n! rowspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center; width:200px;\"|Single\n! style=\"