 =\n{{DirectorsGuildofAmericaOutstandingDirectingDramaSeries}}\n{{EmmyAward DirectingDrama}}\n}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sapochnik, Miguel}}\n[[Category:1974 births]]\n[[Category:British expatriates in the United States]]\n[[Category:British film directors]]\n[[Category:British music video directors]]\n[[Category:British television directors]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:British storyboard artists]]\n[[Category:People from Hammersmith]]\n[[Category:Primetime Emmy Award winners]]\n[[Category:English people of Argentine descent]]\n[[Category:British Jews]]\n", "name_user": "Diopic", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eTelevision credits:add info about awards", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Miguel_Sapochnik"}
{"title_page": "Do You Believe in Magic (album)", "text_new": "{{Infobox album\n| name       = Do You Believe in Magic\n| type       = studio\n| artist     = [[The Lovin' Spoonful]]\n| cover      = Do you believe in magic.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = November 1965\n| recorded   = June 1965 - September 1965\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Folk rock]]<ref name=\"Christgau\"/>\n| length     = 29:58\n| label      = [[Kama Sutra Records|Kama Sutra]]\n| producer   = [[Erik Jacobsen]]\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title = [[Daydream (The Lovin' Spoonful album)|Daydream]]\n| next_year  = 1966\n| misc       = {{Singles\n | name        = Do You Believe in Magic\n | type        = studio\n | single1     = [[Do You Believe in Magic (song)|Do You Believe in Magic]]\n | single1date = July 20, 1965\n | single2     = [[Did You Ever Have to Make Up Your Mind?]]\n | single2date = April 30, 1966\n}}\n}}\n\n'''''Do You Believe in Magic''''' is the debut album by the [[folk rock]] group [[The Lovin' Spoonful]].  It was released in November 1965, on the [[Kama Sutra Records|Kama Sutra]] label. The album features the hits \"[[Do You Believe in Magic (song)|Do You Believe in Magic]]\" (U.S. No. 9) and \"[[Did You Ever Have to Make Up Your Mind?]]\" (U.S. No. 2).\n\n''Do You Believe in Magic'' was re-released on CD in 2002 with five bonus tracks.\n\n==Reception==\n{{Album ratings\n| rev1 =[[Allmusic]]\n| rev1Score = {{Rating|4.5|5}} <ref name=\"AM\">{{cite web |first=William |last=Ruhlman |title= ''Do You Believe in Magic'' > Review |url={{Allmusic|class=album|id= r43645 |pure_url=yes}} |publisher=[[Allmusic]] |accessdate=June 15, 2011}}</ref>\n| rev2 = ''[[MSN Music]]'' ([[Robert Christgau#Consumer Guide|Consumer Guide]])\n| rev2Score = A\u2013<ref name=\"Christgau\">{{cite web|last=Christgau|first=Robert|authorlink=Robert Christgau|date=March 29, 2013|url=https://www.robertchristgau.com/xg/cg/ew2013-03.php|title=The Lovin' Spoonful|work=[[MSN Music]]|accessdate=March 30, 2013}}</ref>\n| rev3 = ''[[Encyclopedia of Popular Music]]''\n| rev3Score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref>{{cite book|last=Larkin|first=Colin|authorlink=Colin Larkin|title=Encyclopedia of Popular Music|year=2007|publisher=[[Oxford University Press]]|edition=4th|isbn=978-0195313734|title-link=Encyclopedia of Popular Music}}</ref>\n}}\nIn his [[Allmusic]] review, music critic William Ruhlmann wrote \"The album elaborated upon Sebastian's gentle, winning songwriting style... The album also revealed the group's jug band roots in its arrangements of traditional songs... The Spoonful would be remembered as a vehicle for Sebastian's songwriting, but ''Do You Believe in Magic'' was a well-rounded collection that demonstrated their effectiveness as a group.\"<ref name=\"AM\" />\n\n==Track listing==\n{{Track listing\n| total_length    = \n| title1          = [[Do You Believe in Magic (song)|Do You Believe in Magic]]\n| writer1         = [[John Sebastian]]\n| length1         = 2:07\n| title2          = Blues in the Bottle\n| writer2         = Traditional\n| length2         = 2:12\n| title3          = Sportin' Life\n| writer3         = Traditional\n| length3         = 4:04\n| title4          = My Gal\n| writer4         = Traditional\n| length4         = 2:38\n| title5          = You Baby\n| writer5         = [[Barry Mann]], [[Phil Spector]], [[Cynthia Weil]]\n| length5         = 2:56\n| title6          = [[Fishin' Blues]]\n| writer6         = Traditional\n| length6         = 2:02\n| title7          = [[Did You Ever Have to Make Up Your Mind?]]\n| writer7         = Sebastian\n| length7         = 1:59\n| title8          = Wild About My Lovin'\n| writer8         = Traditional\n| length8         = 2:36\n| title9          = Other Side of This Life\n| writer9         = [[Fred Neil]]\n| length9         = 2:30\n| title10          = [[Younger Girl]]\n| writer10         = Sebastian\n| length10         = 2:20\n| title11          = On the Road Again\n| writer11         = Sebastian\n| length11         = 1:51\n| title12          = Night Owl Blues\n| writer12         = Steve Boone, [[Joe Butler]], Sebastian, [[Zal Yanovsky]]\n| length12         = 3:05\n}}\n{{Track listing\n| collapsed       = yes\n| headline        = Bonus tracks on 2002 reissue\n| total_length    = \n| title13          = [[Alley Oop (song)|Alley Oop]]\n| writer13         = [[Dallas Frazier]]\n| length13         = 2:17\n| title14          = Younger Girl\n| note14           = Demo\n| writer14         = Sebastian\n| length14         = 2:39\n| title15          = Blues in the Bottle\n| note15           = Alternate Vocal\n| writer15         = Traditional\n| length15         = 3:02\n| title16          = Wild About My Lovin'\n| note16           = Alternate Vocal\n| writer16         = Traditional\n| length16         = 2:36\n| title17          = Other Side of This Life\n| note17           = Instrumental\n| writer17         = Neil\n| length17         = 2:31\n}}\n\n==Personnel==\n*[[John Sebastian]] \u2013 vocals, guitar, [[autoharp]], harmonica, organ\n*[[Steve Boone]] \u2013 bass, vocals\n*[[Joe Butler]] \u2013 drums, percussion, vocals\n*[[Zal Yanovsky]] \u2013 electric and acoustic guitar, vocals\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:The Lovin' Spoonful albums]]\n[[Category:1965 debut albums]]\n[[Category:Kama Sutra Records albums]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Erik Jacobsen]]\n\n{{The Lovin' Spoonful}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox album\n| name       = Do You Believe in Magic\n| type       = studio\n| artist     = [[The Lovin' Spoonful]]\n| cover      = Do you believe in magic.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = November 1965\n| recorded   = June 1965 - September 1965\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Folk rock]]<ref name=\"Christgau\"/>\n| length     = 29:58\n| label      = [[Kama Sutra Records|Kama Sutra]]\n| producer   = [[Erik Jacobsen]]\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title = [[Daydream (The Lovin' Spoonful album)|Daydream]]\n| next_year  = 1966\n| misc       = {{Singles\n | name        = Do You Believe in Magic\n | type        = studio\n | single1     = [[Do You Believe in Magic (song)|Do You Believe in Magic]]\n | single1date = July 20, 1965\n | single2     = [[Did You Ever Have to Make Up Your Mind?]]\n | single2date = April 30, 1966\n}}\n}}\n\n'''''Do You Believe in Magic''''' is the debut album by the [[folk rock]] group [[The Lovin' Spoonful]].  It was released in November 1965, on the [[Kama Sutra Records|Kama Sutra]] label. The album features the hits \"[[Do You Believe in Magic (song)|Do You Believe in Magic]]\" (U.S. No. 9) and \"[[Did You Ever Have to Make Up Your Mind?]]\" (U.S. No. 2).\n\n''Do You Believe in Magic'' was re-released on CD in 2002 with five bonus tracks.\n\n==Reception==\n{{Album ratings\n| rev1 =[[Allmusic]]\n| rev1Score = {{Rating|4.5|5}} <ref name=\"AM\">{{cite web |first=William |last=Ruhlman |title= ''Do You Believe in Magic'' > Review |url={{Allmusic|class=album|id= r43645 |pure_url=yes}} |publisher=[[Allmusic]] |accessdate=June 15, 2011}}</ref>\n| rev2 = ''[[MSN Music]]'' ([[Robert Christgau#Consumer Guide|Consumer Guide]])\n| rev2Score = A\u2013<ref name=\"Christgau\">{{cite web|last=Christgau|first=Robert|authorlink=Robert Christgau|date=March 29, 2013|url=https://www.robertchristgau.com/xg/cg/ew2013-03.php|title=The Lovin' Spoonful|work=[[MSN Music]]|accessdate=March 30, 2013}}</ref>\n}}\nIn his [[Allmusic]] review, music critic William Ruhlmann wrote \"The album elaborated upon Sebastian's gentle, winning songwriting style... The album also revealed the group's jug band roots in its arrangements of traditional songs... The Spoonful would be remembered as a vehicle for Sebastian's songwriting, but ''Do You Believe in Magic'' was a well-rounded collection that demonstrated their effectiveness as a group.\"<ref name=\"AM\" />\n\n==Track listing==\n{{Track listing\n| total_length    = \n| title1          = [[Do You Believe in Magic (song)|Do You Believe in Magic]]\n| writer1   